  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin.",
  "response_text": "To calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin, we can use the binomial probability formula. The formula is:\n\nP(X = k) = (nCk) * (p^k) * (q^(n-k))\n\nWhere:\n- P(X = k) is the probability of getting exactly k successes (in this case, heads)\n- n is the number of trials (5 coin flips)\n- k is the number of successes (3 heads)\n- nCk is the number of combinations of n items taken k at a time (calculated as n! / (k! * (n-k)!) )\n- p is the probability of success (0.5 for a fair coin, since there's a 50% chance of getting heads)\n- q is the probability of failure (0.5 for a fair coin, since there's a 50% chance of getting tails)\n\nFirst, we need to calculate the number of combinations of 5 items taken 3 at a time:\n5C3 = 5! / (3! * (5-3)!)\n= 5! / (3! * 2!)\n= (5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1) / ((3 * 2 * 1) * (2 * 1))\n= (120) / ((6) * (2))\n= 120 / 12\n= 10\n\nNow, we can plug in the values into the binomial probability formula:\nP(X = 3) = (10) * (0.5^3) * (0.5^(5-3))\n= 10 * (0.125) * (0.5^2)\n= 10 * (0.125) * (0.25)\n= 10 * 0.03125\n= 0.3125\n\nTherefore, the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin is 0.3125 or 31.25%.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 7\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
